{{Infobox newspaper | name = Bota Sot | image = Bota Sot Newspaper logo.jpg | image_size = 150 | caption = | type = Daily [[newspaper]] | format = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]] | foundation = 1995 | ceased publication = | price = 0.20€ | owner = Media Print | political position = Pro: [[Democratic League of Kosovo|LDK]], [[Ibrahim Rugova|Rugovism]], [[Democratic Party of Albania|PDSH]], [[Sali Berisha]] | publisher = Mazrekaj Media<ref name="BotaSotContact">[http://www.botasot.info/kontakt/ Editorial]</ref> | editor = Idriz Morina<ref name="BotaSotContact"/> | staff = 45 | circulation = 13.000 Daily | headquarters = [[Zürich]], [[Prishtina]] | ISSN = | website = {{URL|http://www.botasot.info}} }} '''''Bota Sot''''' (English: World Today) is a daily [[newspaper]] from [[Kosovo]], originally published by members of the Kosovo diaspora in Switzerland.
==History==
''Bota Sot'' is published by Media Print and is owned by Xhevdet Mazrekaj, a diaspora businessman. The newspaper was published for the first time in 1995, and initially solely published abroad. The paper editorially supports the [[Democratic Party of Albania]] and has supported two previous presidents of Kosovo from that party, [[Ibrahim Rugova]] and [[Sali Berisha]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Attacks on the Press in 2001 - Yugoslavia |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/category,COI,CPJ,ANNUALREPORT,MNE,47c5664f24,0.html |publisher=United Nations High Commission for Refugees |accessdate=15 May 2011 |date=February 2002 |quote=the Geneva-based Bota Sot, supports politician Ibrahim Rugova and his leading ethnic Albanian party, the Democratic Alliance of Kosovo. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018133210/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/category%2CCOI%2CCPJ%2CANNUALREPORT%2CMNE%2C47c5664f24%2C0.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>
A number of the newspaper's journalists have been assassinated. [[Xhemail Mustafa]], a journalist and advisor to President Rugova, was assassinated in November, 2000. ''Bota Sot'' journalist Bekim Kastrati was assassinated in October, 2001, along with two other men who were in his car at the time, in the village of Lauša, near [[Prishtina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Attacks on the Press in 2001 - Yugoslavia |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/category,COI,CPJ,ANNUALREPORT,MNE,47c5664f24,0.html |publisher=United Nations High Commission for Refugees |accessdate=15 May 2011 |date=February 2002 |quote=Bekim Kastrati, Bota Sot KILLED (motive unconfirmed) Kastrati, an ethnic Albanian journalist for the Albanian-language daily Bota Sot, was shot on October 19 at around 8 p.m. in the village of Lausa, west of the provincial capital, Pristina, along with two other men who were riding in his car at the time. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018133210/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/category%2CCOI%2CCPJ%2CANNUALREPORT%2CMNE%2C47c5664f24%2C0.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 |df= }}</ref> [[Bardhyl Ajeti]] wrote daily editorials for ''Bota Sot'', supporting the anticrime campaign of international authorities in arresting former members of the [[Kosova Liberation Army]] (KLA).<ref>{{cite web|title=Bardhyl Ajeti|url=http://www.cpj.org/killed/2005/bardhyl-ajeti.php|publisher=CPJ|accessdate=8 May 2011|quote=Ajeti wrote daily editorials for Bota Sot..supported international authorities who arrested former members of the Kosova Liberation Army (KLA) as part of a broader anticrime campaign,...}}</ref> He was shot by unidentified assassins in June 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=IHF report 2006 - Human rights in OSCE region|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/pdfid/4693929a0.pdf|accessdate=8 May 2011|pages=362–363|year=2006|quote=On 25 June, Bardhyl Ajeti, a prominent journalist of one of the major Kosovo newspapers, died of gunshot wounds he had sustained on 3 June: he was shot by unidentified assassins while traveling to-ward Prishtina from his home town of Gnjilane.}}</ref>
