{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = The Papers of Tony Veitch | image = The Papers of Tony Veitch.jpg | image_size = | border = | caption = | alt = | author = [[William McIlvanney]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = Laidlaw #2 | subject = | genre = | publisher = [[Hodder & Stoughton|Hodder and Stoughton]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = 1983<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = 0340229071 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = [[Laidlaw (novel)]] | preceded_by_quotation_marks = | followed_by = [[Strange Loyalties]] | followed_by_quotation_marks = | wikisource = }} '''''The Papers of Tony Veitch''''' is a crime novel by [[William McIlvanney]]. This book is the second in the series featuring the character Laidlaw.<ref name=SASLS>{{cite web|last=Dickson|first=Beth|title=William McIlvanney’s Laidlaw Novels|url=http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/scotlit/asls/Laverock-McIlvanney-2.html|publisher=The Association for Scottish Literary Studies|accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref> This series of books is recognised as the foundation of the [[Tartan Noir]] genre.<ref name=TelegraphCamus>{{cite news|last=Massie|first=Allan|title=Scotland's master of crime is also its Camus|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/10080000/Scotlands-master-of-crime-is-also-its-Camus.html|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=25 May 2013}}</ref>
==Plot== Jack Laidlaw visits the deathbed of an alcoholic vagrant Eck Adamson who provides a cryptic last message which helps solve the murder of a gangland thug and the disappearance of a student. In the process, Laidlaw uncovers widespread corruption.
==Editions== The book was first published in 1983 by [[Hodder & Staughton]], and was reissued on 3 June 2013 by [[Canongate Books]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Papers of Tony Veitch|url=http://www.canongate.tv/the-papers-of-tony-veitch.html|publisher=Canongate|accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref>
